{"PubmedArticle": [{"MedlineCitation": {"InvestigatorList": [], "SpaceFlightMission": [], "CitationSubset": ["IM"], "KeywordList": [], "GeneralNote": [], "OtherAbstract": [], "OtherID": [], "PMID": "3566272", "DateCompleted": {"Year": "1987", "Month": "05", "Day": "13"}, "DateRevised": {"Year": "2021", "Month": "05", "Day": "26"}, "Article": {"Language": ["eng"], "ELocationID": [], "ArticleDate": [], "Journal": {"ISSN": "0099-2240", "JournalIssue": {"Volume": "53", "Issue": "2", "PubDate": {"Year": "1987", "Month": "Feb"}}, "Title": "Applied and environmental microbiology", "ISOAbbreviation": "Appl Environ Microbiol"}, "ArticleTitle": "Comparative assessment of chlorine, heat, ozone, and UV light for killing Legionella pneumophila within a model plumbing system.", "Pagination": {"StartPage": "447", "EndPage": "453", "MedlinePgn": "447-53"}, "Abstract": {"AbstractText": ["Nosocomial Legionnaires disease can be acquired by exposure to the organism from the hospital water distribution system. As a result, many hospitals have instituted eradication procedures, including hypercholorination and thermal eradication. We compared the efficacy of ozonation, UV light, hyperchlorination, and heat eradication using a model plumbing system constructed of copper piping, brass spigots, Plexiglas reservoir, electric hot water tank, and a pump. Legionella pneumophila was added to the system at 10(7) CFU/ml. Each method was tested under three conditions; (i) nonturbid water at 25 degrees C, (ii) turbid water at 25 degrees C, and (iii) nonturbid water at 43 degrees C. UV light and heat killed L. pneumophila most rapidly and required minimal maintenance. Both UV light and heat (60 degrees C) produced a 5 log kill in less than 1 h. In contrast, both chlorine and ozone required 5 h of exposure to produce a 5 log decrease. Neither turbidity nor the higher temperature of 43 degrees C impaired the efficacy of any of the disinfectant methods. Surprisingly, higher temperature enhanced the disinfecting efficacy of chlorine. However, higher temperature accelerated the decomposition of the chlorine residual such that an additional 120% volume of chlorine was required. All four methods proved efficacious in eradicating L. pneumophila from a model plumbing system."]}, "AuthorList": [{"AffiliationInfo": [], "Identifier": [], "LastName": "Muraca", "ForeName": "P", "Initials": "P"}, {"AffiliationInfo": [], "Identifier": [], "LastName": "Stout", "ForeName": "J E", "Initials": "JE"}, {"AffiliationInfo": [], "Identifier": [], "LastName": "Yu", "ForeName": "V L", "Initials": "VL"}], "PublicationTypeList": ["Comparative Study", "Journal Article", "Research Support, U.S. Gov't, Non-P.H.S."]}, "MedlineJournalInfo": {"Country": "United States", "MedlineTA": "Appl Environ Microbiol", "NlmUniqueID": "7605801", "ISSNLinking": "0099-2240"}, "ChemicalList": [{"RegistryNumber": "4R7X1O2820", "NameOfSubstance": "Chlorine"}, {"RegistryNumber": "66H7ZZK23N", "NameOfSubstance": "Ozone"}], "MeshHeadingList": [{"QualifierName": ["pharmacology"], "DescriptorName": "Chlorine"}, {"QualifierName": [], "DescriptorName": "Disinfection"}, {"QualifierName": [], "DescriptorName": "Hot Temperature"}, {"QualifierName": ["drug effects", "radiation effects"], "DescriptorName": "Legionella"}, {"QualifierName": ["pharmacology"], "DescriptorName": "Ozone"}, {"QualifierName": [], "DescriptorName": "Sanitary Engineering"}, {"QualifierName": [], "DescriptorName": "Sterilization"}, {"QualifierName": [], "DescriptorName": "Ultraviolet Rays"}, {"QualifierName": [], "DescriptorName": "Water Microbiology"}]}, "PubmedData": {"ReferenceList": [{"ReferenceList": [], "Reference": [{"Citation": "Appl Environ Microbiol. 1979 Aug;38(2):347-8", "ArticleIdList": ["518088"]}, {"Citation": "Arch Intern Med. 1986 Aug;146(8):1607-12", "ArticleIdList": ["3524495"]}, {"Citation": "J Infect Dis. 1980 Jun;141(6):727-32", "ArticleIdList": ["7391615"]}, {"Citation": "N Engl J Med. 1982 Feb 25;306(8):466-8", "ArticleIdList":